         <div type="commentary" subtype="frontmatter" xml:space="preserve">
        <p>Four fragments of this papyrus sheet survive, containing, as the editor says, "a rather mixed up version of Joannes Chrysostomus' In epistulam I ad Corinthios." In relation to Migne PG 61 the order of the several text elements seems at random, moreover on some places the scribe's text departs from the Migne text. The text on the verso is written upside down in relation to the text on the recto. The order in which the text is presented is therefore unusual: the front sides of fragments 1 and 2, followed by the back sides of fragments 2 and 1. The editor has joined the second and third fragments to create ‘fragment 2’, which the fourth and final fragment is unplaced and has been named ‘fragment 3’ for this purposes of its DCLP transcription.”</p>
      </div>
